  "prompt": "Which sect of Jews lived in Macca and Madinah during the time of Prophet Muhammad?",
  "response": "During the time of Prophet Muhammad, the Jews living in Mecca and Medina primarily belonged to different tribes rather than specific sects. In Medina, there were three main Jewish tribes: Banu Qaynuqa, Banu Nadir, and Banu Qurayza. These tribes were not identified by specific religious sects but rather by their tribal affiliations.\n\nIn Mecca, there were fewer Jews compared to Medina, and they were not organized into distinct tribes like those in Medina. The Jewish presence in Mecca was more scattered and less influential.\n\nIt's important to note that during this period, the concept of Jewish sects as we understand it today (such as Pharisees, Sadducees, or later groups like the Karaites and Rabbanites) was not as clearly defined or relevant in the Arabian Peninsula. The Jews in Mecca and Medina were primarily identified by their tribal affiliations and their adherence to Judaism in a broader sense.",
